description: This 1968 Ford Mustang offers a terrific V8 rumble, a standout color package, and other nice upgrades.  So when an iconic classic can be powerful, thoughtful, and affordable, you know it has serious appeal.

The color you see here is a fine representation of 1968's Meadowlark Yellow.  It's a great way to stand out while still following the heritage of the Mustang.  But the real reason why it works so well here is that it provides a bright and sunny disposition to an aggressively packaged pony car.  After all, the yellow is the perfect color for the contrasting blacked-out grille and blacked-out inserts in the deluxe hood. Plus, the those 15-inch Eagle Alloys draw extra attention to the intimidating forward-leaning stance.  So the yellow is like a friendly face luring you into a dark corner.

Inside there are more great upgrades.  The factory-correct black interior continues to look nice, and so it was easy to integrate some modern components.  After all, no one could get bucket seats with that kind of bolstering in '68.  These new additions can hug your body in the corners and provide all-day comfort.   Plus, the cup holder center console and grippy sports steering wheel on the tilt column come together to create an environment that envelops the driver.  It's an impressive upgraded performance package.  So while you have provisions for R134a air conditioning and an upgraded stereo, you're real focus will be on the white-faced gauges.

Ford's 289 cubic-inch V8 is one of those great power plants that's exceptionally reliable, and it's always ready for a few upgrades.  We're happy to see an investment in components like an Edelbrock four-barrel carburetor, Edelbrock Performer intake, and Mustang fined valve covers.  This V8 has been maintained correctly, so it fires up with gusto, and it make a nice throaty rumble out of the Thursh dual exhaust.  Out on the road, the three-speed automatic transmission, power steering, front disc brakes, and BF Goodrich T/A tires come together to make for the perfect cruising package.
This is the cool Mustang that has been upgraded for a unique performance appearance, extra power, and plenty of rumble.  That makes it a great package for a quite a nice price. Call now!

This Shelby was carefully restored to factory specifications during 1994-1995. Ford NOS parts were sourced to insure a high quality restoration. All the rare fiberglass panels are correct Shelby parts, not reproductions. This vehicle has the proper Ram Air-cleaner. The goal of the owner was to restore the Shelby to new condition and rebuild all mechanics so the car would be dependable and a joy to travel in. One of the most collectible Shelbys ever produced. Only 517 late convertibles were made. These cars debuted with the ferocious 428 Cobra Jet Engine, equipped with rare bore cast iron exhaust manifolds and improved carburetion and heads. This particular Shelby was one of the few with Special Order Yellow color. Factory equipment includes, Automatic, Power Steering, Power Brakes, Tilt and Swing-A-Way steering wheel, and Deluxe interior. Radio has been up-dated with a period correct Am-FM. The 68 Shelby unique features include floor console, factory oil and ammeter gauges, padded roll bar with inertial reels for race style shoulder belts. Shelby body styling was unique for 1968 with fiberglass hood, trunk lid, lower quarter panel side scoops. History: The 68 KR convertible was built at Fords Metuchen, New Jersey plant and shipped to A.O. Smith in Inonia, Michigan, for final assembly. Fords New Jersey plant was responsible for building the chassis complete with mechanics. A.O Smith finished the 68 Shelbys installing the intake, Car Fiberglas Body panels, and Unique Shelby interior parts.

This early production, low mileage  Mustang 2+2 has it's original Poppy Red finish and Parchment interior. It is totally original and is equipped with the C-code 289 cu in V-8, 3 speed manual transmission and factory air conditioning. Other options include chrome engine dress up kit and wheel covers with spinners. This car has undergone a frame off restoration, and has 1300 miles since it's completion, While the engine has 3800 since being rebuilt. The restoration was completed in July 1998. This show car has won 1st place in every show entered and has won the Peoples Choice Award 6 time. I has been part of a private collection since 2003 and kept in a climate controlled garage ever since. The first-generation Ford Mustang was manufactured by Ford from March 1964 until 1973. The introduction of the Mustang created a new class of automobile known as the pony car. The Mustang's styling, with its long hood and short deck, proved wildly popular and inspired a host of competition. The 1965 and 1966 Mustang Fastback was marketed as the "Mustang 2+2", because it came with, as standard equipment, a fold-down rear seat. The car even had chrome fender emblems "MUSTANG 2+2" in the location where other body styles had a plain "MUSTANG" emblem. In 1967, the seat became optional, and the "2+2" designation was dropped.
1965 Ford Mustang Convertible | Ardell Brown Classic Cars www.ardellscars.com/1965-ford-mustang-convertible/

This early 1965 convertible Mustang is powered by the "D" code 289 4V engine, and automatic transmission. It is presented in Rangoon Red and is equipped with a power convertible top with a rear glass window, power disc brakes, power steering, factory air conditioning, wood grain console, and original radio is in the trunk. The standard interior features of the 1965 Mustang included adjustable driver and passenger bucket seats, an AM radio, and a floor mounted shifter in a variety of color options. Ford added additional interior options during the 1965 model year. The Interior Decor Group was popularly known as "Pony Interior" due to the addition of embossed running ponies on the seat fronts, and also included integral armrests, woodgrain appliqué accents, and a round gauge cluster that would replace the standard Falcon instrumentation. Also available were sun visors, a (mechanical) remote-operated mirror, a floor console, and a bench seat. Ford later offered an under-dash air-conditioning unit, and discontinued the vinyl with cloth insert seat option, offered only in early 1965 models.

This Mustang is an excellent example of the early production Mustang cars. It is presented in Rangoon Red with black bucket seat interior. Much detail was put into this Mustang to make it as nice as possible. It features the "D" code 289 V-8 and a 3 speed Cruise-o-matic transmission. The interior has bucket seats and center console. The optional wire wheel covers really add to the sporty look. This Mustang is ready to enjoy. The Ford Mustang was brought out five months before the normal start of the 1965 production year. The early production versions are often referred to as "1964½ models" but all Mustangs were advertised, VIN coded and titled by Ford as 1965 models, though minor design updates for fall 1965 contribute to tracking 1964½ production data separately from 1965 data with production beginning in Dearborn, Michigan on March 9, 1964;the new car was introduced to the public on April 17, 1964 at the New York World's Fair.

This beautiful 1965 Ford Guardsman Blue K-Code convertible has been fully restored. It is the correct solid lifter, high performance 289 cu in V-8 with 4 speed manual transmission. Options include chrome Styled steel wheels and Rallye Pac gauge cluster. People often ask how the K-Code engine was different from the other D,C, and A code 289 engines featured in 1965-1967 Mustangs. This engine featured upgraded pistons, cylinder heads, carburetor, lifter heads, and connecting rods. In addition, one look under the hood and you'd notice the chrome air cleaner and valve covers. With an estimated 271 hp at its disposal, it was easy to tell this car from other 289 powered Mustangs of the day.

This 1968 Ford Mustang GT/CS is powered by the 289 cu in V-8 and has a 4 speed manual transmission. The roof has been signed by Carrol Shelby. Shelby Automotive, now part of Ford, was assigned the task of designing and engineering the necessary parts and assembly procedures for the GT/CS. This was done right alongside the development of their 1968 Shelby. The fiberglass parts were crafted at A.O. Smith, in Ionia, Michigan, in steel molds. A.O. Smith was also the same OEM manufacturer for the Corvette fiberglass bodies. The fiberglass parts for the GT/CS included: the rear decklid and end caps, taillight panel, and side scoops.

This 1968 Ford Mustang is an original restored car powered by the 302 V8 and Automatic Transmission. It has power steering and STOCK wheels with full wheel covers.The paint is laser straight and a new all vinyl bucket seat interior with a well fitted convertible top boot. Changes for the 1968 model increased safety with a two-spoke energy-absorbing steering wheel, along with newly introduced shoulder belts. Other changes included front and rear side markers, "FORD" lettering removed from hood, rearview mirror moved from frame to windshield and a 302 cu in V8 engine was now available.
